% ABSTRACT
%------------------------------------------------------------
\newpage
\chapter*{Abstract}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Abstract}

Indian classical dance encompasses eight government-recognised forms —
Bharatanatyam, Kathak, Odissi, Kuchipudi, Manipuri, Mohiniyattam, Sattriya,
and Kathakali — each defined by unique body postures, hand gestures (mudras),
and temporal rhythmic patterns. Automated recognition of these forms is a
challenging fine-grained action recognition problem due to significant
inter-class visual similarity and the critical discriminative role of hand
and foot micro-gestures.

This project presents NatyaVeda v2, an end-to-end AI system for classifying
all eight Indian classical dance forms from video. The pipeline combines a
multi-tier pose extraction stage, a mudra-aware hand feature stage, and a
Transformer-based temporal classifier called DanceFormer. Pose extraction
employs VitPose-Plus (133 COCO-WholeBody keypoints, 125.4M parameters) as
the primary extractor, with MMPose RTMW-x as the high-VRAM tier and MoveNet
Thunder as a CPU fallback, ensuring deployment across a wide range of hardware.
VideoMAE-Large (343M parameters, MCG-NJU) provides global appearance-motion
features. The DanceFormer architecture uses 8 Transformer layers, 8 attention
heads, and a 1024-dimensional feed-forward network, trained with a
six-component combined loss: Focal dance classification, Supervised
Contrastive, Center, Inter-class Push, Angular Orthogonal, and Mudra
Cross-Entropy losses.

The system achieves a test-set accuracy of \textbf{97.49\%}, a weighted
F1-score of \textbf{0.9749}, and a macro F1-score of \textbf{0.9766} across
all eight classes on the current 2,914-clip test split generated from the
processed dataset. Bharatanatyam, Manipuri, Sattriya, and Kathakali all reach
per-class F1 scores above 0.97. The prototype calibration approach yields
measurable improvement without model retraining.

\vspace{0.8cm}
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} Indian classical dance, pose estimation,
hand gesture recognition, DanceFormer, VitPose, Transformer, supervised
contrastive learning, mudra, fine-grained action recognition, prototype
calibration

