\chapter{Introduction}

\section{Background and Motivation}

India's classical dance tradition spans over two millennia, documented in the
Natyashastra of Bharata Muni (2nd century BCE). The Sangeet Natak Akademi
recognises eight major forms — Bharatanatyam, Kathak, Odissi, Kuchipudi,
Manipuri, Mohiniyattam, Sattriya, and Kathakali — each with its own canonical
grammar of body postures, hand gestures (hastas or mudras), facial expressions
(abhinaya), and rhythmic footwork patterns. Despite their cultural significance,
no large-scale automated system exists that can classify all eight forms
reliably from raw video.

The practical value of such a system is substantial: it can support digital
archiving of rare performance recordings, assist teaching platforms by providing
pose and gesture feedback, enable dance research through quantitative analysis
of style evolution, and power cultural heritage preservation initiatives. Beyond
the applied domain, this problem serves as a rigorous test-bench for fine-grained
action recognition in computer vision, because the visual differences between
dance forms are subtle, involving limb angles, spinal curvature, and hand
micro-gestures that standard action recognition datasets do not contain.

\section{Problem Statement}

Recognising Indian classical dance forms from video is a fine-grained,
multi-class action recognition problem with several distinguishing challenges:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Fine-grained visual similarity}: Mohiniyattam and Kuchipudi,
    both soft Kerala/Andhra forms, share flowing movements and similar costuming.
    Kathak and Kathakali both involve elaborate hand sequences. Standard action
    recognition features based on optical flow or global appearance are
    insufficient for reliable discrimination.
    
    \item \textbf{Hand gesture criticality}: The 28 canonical mudras (hasta
    gestures) defined in Natyashastra are the primary discriminative signal for
    several class pairs. Standard human pose estimation models predict only 17
    body keypoints (COCO format) and miss the 21-point hand skeleton entirely.
    
    \item \textbf{Temporal structure}: Dance forms differ not only in spatial pose
    but in temporal rhythm --- the chakkar spinning of Kathak, the tribhangi wave
    of Odissi, and the aramandi stance transitions of Bharatanatyam require
    multi-frame context.
    
    \item \textbf{Data scarcity}: Unlike ImageNet or Kinetics, no labelled
    Indian classical dance video dataset exists at sufficient scale. Collecting,
    annotating, and cleaning performance videos requires a bespoke pipeline.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Project Objectives}

This project addresses the above challenges through four core objectives:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Design and implement a complete end-to-end pipeline from raw YouTube
    video download to trained inference, covering data collection, refinement,
    feature extraction, model training, evaluation, and deployment.
    
    \item Develop a multi-tier pose extraction architecture that provides 133-point
    COCO-WholeBody keypoints (including full hand, foot, and face landmarks)
    across varying hardware configurations, with automatic tier selection based
    on available GPU memory.
    
    \item Train a DanceFormer Transformer classifier with a multi-component loss
    function specifically designed to maximise inter-class separation for
    visually similar dance pairs identified from confusion matrix analysis.
    
    \item Achieve a test accuracy above 90\% across all eight dance forms, with
    validated prototype-based inference calibration that further improves
    classification at the boundary between confused pairs.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Key Contributions}

The principal technical contributions of this project are:

\begin{itemize}
    \item A \textbf{multi-tier pose extraction framework} combining VitPose-Plus
    (Hugging Face), RTMW-x (MMPose), and MoveNet Thunder (TensorFlow Hub) under
    a unified \texttt{PoseExtractor} API with automatic hardware-based tier
    selection.
    
    \item A \textbf{confusion-matrix-driven loss system} incorporating Inter-class
    Push Loss, which directly penalises proximity between class prototype embeddings
    of empirically identified confused pairs (Mohiniyattam--Kuchipudi,
    Kathak--Kathakali, Odissi--Bharatanatyam).
    
    \item A \textbf{prototype-based inference calibration} method that blends
    DanceFormer logits with cosine similarity scores to learned class prototypes,
    improving boundary-case accuracy without retraining.
    
    \item A \textbf{fully reproducible pipeline} with documented dependency
    pinning for Python 3.10 on Windows and Linux, resolving known compatibility
    issues between NumPy, OpenCV, MMPose, MediaPipe, and TensorFlow.
\end{itemize}

