% CHAPTER 2: LITERATURE REVIEW
%------------------------------------------------------------
\chapter{Literature Review}

\section{Skeleton-Based Action Recognition}

Skeleton-based action recognition has evolved from hand-crafted joint features
to deep learning methods. Early Graph Convolutional Network approaches such as
ST-GCN~\cite{yan2018} modelled joint relationships as a spatial graph with
temporal convolutions, achieving competitive results on NTU RGB+D. More recent
works explored Transformer architectures for long-range temporal dependency
modelling. The Hierarchical Consistent Contrastive Learning framework
(HiCLR)~\cite{zhang2022} applied asymmetric contrastive learning with growing
augmentation strength to skeleton sequences, improving cluster formation in
representation space. The STARS self-supervised tuning method~\cite{mehraban2024}
combined masked prediction with nearest-neighbour contrastive learning to improve
cluster formation for skeleton-based recognition, directly motivating our use of
Supervised Contrastive Loss during DanceFormer training.

\section{Whole-Body Pose Estimation}

Standard human pose estimation delivers 17 body keypoints (COCO format) but
misses the hand and face regions critical for gesture-rich domains such as dance.
COCO-WholeBody~\cite{jin2020} extended the annotation standard to 133 keypoints
covering body, face, hands, and feet. RTMPose and its whole-body variant
RTMW~\cite{yang2023} demonstrated real-time 133-point extraction using a
SimCC-based regression head.

ViTPose~\cite{xu2022a} and ViTPose++~\cite{xu2022b} showed that plain Vision
Transformers without task-specific modules achieve state-of-the-art performance
on human pose estimation, motivating the selection of VitPose-Plus (Hugging Face
\texttt{usyd-community/vitpose-plus-base}, 125.4M parameters) as the primary
pose extractor in our multi-tier architecture. The model is natively available
via the Hugging Face Transformers library, enabling deployment without MMPose
compilation on restricted hardware.

\section{Video Representation Learning}

VideoMAE~\cite{tong2022} proposed masked autoencoders for self-supervised video
pre-training, achieving strong performance on action recognition benchmarks with
high tube masking ratios. The VideoMAE-Large model (MCG-NJU, 343M parameters)
provides global appearance-motion representations complementing the local
keypoint features of pose extraction. In NatyaVeda, VideoMAE features are fused
into the DanceFormer classifier to capture holistic style information
(e.g., costumes, stage lighting variations) that may not be apparent from
skeleton keypoints alone.

\section{Person Detection for Top-Down Pose Estimation}

Top-down pose estimation requires a person bounding box. We use the DETR
(DEtection TRansformer)~\cite{carion2020} architecture via
\texttt{facebook/detr-resnet-50} from the Hugging Face Hub. DETR formulates
object detection as a set prediction problem using Transformer attention over
image features, producing stable bounding boxes without the non-maximum
suppression post-processing required by anchor-based detectors.

\section{Loss Functions for Metric Learning and Cluster Separation}

\textbf{Focal Loss}~\cite{lin2017} addresses class imbalance by down-weighting
well-classified examples, focusing training on hard samples. We use it as the
primary dance classification objective.

\textbf{Supervised Contrastive Loss}~\cite{khosla2020} extends contrastive
learning to the fully supervised setting, pulling together all instances of the
same class while pushing apart instances of different classes in normalised
feature space. Unlike the cross-entropy objective, it operates on the
intermediate feature representation rather than logits, directly shaping the
embedding geometry.

\textbf{Center Loss}~\cite{wen2016} introduced learnable class prototype centres
updated as exponential moving averages during training, with a loss term that
minimises intra-class variance by penalising the distance between a sample's
feature and its class centre.

\textbf{Orthogonal Projection Loss (OPL)}~\cite{ranasinghe2021} enforces
inter-class feature separation by penalising non-zero dot products between
features of different classes in a mini-batch, promoting orthogonality in the
feature space.

\section{Dance and Cultural Heritage Recognition}

Prior work on dance recognition has focused primarily on ballet or fitness
movements (e.g., DeepDance, DancePose). Works on Indian classical dance are
sparse: Rajesh et al.~\cite{rajesh2018} applied HMMs to Bharatanatyam gesture
recognition with 15 gestures; Saha et al.~\cite{saha2018} used CNNs for mudra
classification from static images. No prior work addresses all eight classical
forms from raw video with a unified deep learning pipeline integrating wholebody
133-point pose estimation, temporal modelling, and prototype calibration.

