\section{Video Refinement}

Raw performance videos contain non-dance segments: introductions, audience
reactions, title cards, and intermission footage. The DanceIsolator module
removes these using a three-stage filter:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Scene segmentation}: PySceneDetect (content threshold 40.0)
    splits each video into candidate scenes at camera cuts.
    \item \textbf{Motion scoring}: Optical flow energy (Farneback algorithm) is
    computed per scene. Scenes with insufficient motion (threshold 0.003) are
    discarded as static shots.
    \item \textbf{Activity scoring}: An activity classifier combining motion
    energy and colour variance assigns a dance confidence score. Scenes below
    0.35 confidence are dropped.
\end{enumerate}

A \textit{fast mode} bypassing the DETR person detector was developed to
reduce per-video processing time from $\sim$17 minutes to $\sim$30 seconds on
the available GTX 1650 hardware, enabling practical refinement of all 174 videos.

\section{Feature Extraction}

Each refined video clip was processed through the multi-tier extraction
pipeline (detailed in Chapter~\ref{ch:methodology}) to produce a per-frame
feature array of shape $[T \times 133 \times 3]$ where $T$ is the number of
sampled frames and each of the 133 keypoints carries $(x, y, \text{confidence})$
coordinates. Hand keypoints (indices 91--132) were fused from MediaPipe
Hands at a detection confidence threshold of 0.30. Each processed clip also
carries a velocity tensor ($\Delta$ keypoints) and an acceleration tensor.
Optionally, VideoMAE features of dimension 1024 are stored alongside.

