\chapter{Methodology}
\label{ch:methodology}

\section{System Overview}

The NatyaVeda v2 pipeline is illustrated in Figure~\ref{fig:pipeline}. It
consists of five stages: (1)~video collection and refinement, (2)~multi-tier
pose and hand feature extraction, (3)~feature aggregation and clip assembly,
(4)~DanceFormer training, and (5)~prototype-calibrated inference.

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{system_pipeline.png}
    \caption{NatyaVeda v2 end-to-end pipeline. Raw videos are downloaded,
    refined to retain only dance segments, processed into 133-point keypoint
    sequences with hand fusion and VideoMAE features, then used to train the
    DanceFormer Transformer classifier. At inference, predictions are blended
    with class prototype similarities for calibrated output.}
    \label{fig:pipeline}
\end{figure}

\section{Multi-Tier Pose Extraction}

A unified \texttt{PoseExtractor} API automatically selects the most capable
available model based on GPU VRAM, ensuring consistent 133-point COCO-WholeBody
output regardless of hardware.

\begin{table}[H]
\caption{Pose Extraction Tier Selection}
\label{tab:tiers}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{|c|l|c|c|}
\hline
\textbf{Tier} & \textbf{Model} & \textbf{VRAM Required} & \textbf{Keypoints} \\
\hline
1 & RTMW-x (MMPose COCO-WholeBody)   & $\geq$8 GB  & 133 \\
2 & VitPose-Plus-Huge (Hugging Face)  & $\geq$6 GB  & 133 \\
3 & VitPose-Plus-Large (Hugging Face) & $\geq$4 GB  & 133 \\
4 & VitPose-Plus-Base (Hugging Face)  & $\geq$2 GB or CPU & 133 \\
5 & MoveNet Thunder (TF Hub)          & CPU only    & 17 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Person bounding boxes required for top-down inference are produced by
DETR-ResNet-50 (\texttt{facebook/detr-resnet-50}, 41.6M parameters) via
the Hugging Face Transformers API, removing the dependency on MMDet for tiers
2--4. For the GTX 1650 (4.0 GB VRAM) used in this project, Tier 4
(VitPose-Plus-Base) is selected, providing 133-point whole-body predictions at
$\sim$25 FPS on CUDA.

The \texttt{VitPoseExtractor} follows the top-down paradigm:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item DETR detects all persons; the largest bounding box is taken as the
    principal dancer.
    \item VitPoseForPoseEstimation from the Hugging Face Transformers library
    processes the cropped region and regresses 133 heatmaps.
    \item Keypoints are de-normalised to frame coordinates and stored as
    $(x/W, y/H, \text{confidence})$ triples.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Hand Feature Extraction and Mudra Recognition}

MediaPipe Hands (21 landmarks per hand) is used for fine-grained mudra
discrimination. Given that fast mudra sequences can cause detection failures,
the detection confidence threshold was empirically lowered to 0.30
(from the default 0.50) to increase hand detection density. The 21-point
left and right hand arrays are fused into the 133-point skeleton array at
indices 91--111 (left) and 112--132 (right), replacing the coarser COCO
wrist-only points in that region.

A rule-based \texttt{MudraRecognizer} computes five inter-finger angles
from the hand skeleton and maps them to the 28 hasta categories, providing
auxiliary mudra labels for training without manual annotation.

\section{Feature Aggregation}

Each clip's feature representation is a tensor of shape
$[T \times 399]$, where $T$ is the temporal length (padded or truncated to
64 frames) and 399 = 133 keypoints $\times$ 3 coordinates. An accompanying
velocity tensor $\mathbf{v}[t] = \mathbf{p}[t] - \mathbf{p}[t-1]$ and
acceleration tensor $\mathbf{a}[t] = \mathbf{v}[t] - \mathbf{v}[t-1]$ are
concatenated as additional input channels, providing the DanceFormer encoder
with explicit motion dynamics information. Optionally, a 1024-dimensional
VideoMAE feature per clip is fused via a learnable projection layer.

\section{DanceFormer Architecture}

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{danceformer_architecture.png}
    \caption{DanceFormer architecture. Keypoint sequences are projected into
    a $d=256$ embedding via the PosePatchEmbedding module with learnable
    BodyPartAttentionBias. A standard Transformer encoder (8 layers, 8 heads)
    processes the temporal sequence. The CLS token embedding feeds the dance
    classification head; per-frame embeddings feed the mudra classification
    head. A projection head produces L2-normalised features for contrastive
    training.}
    \label{fig:danceformer}
\end{figure}

\subsection{PosePatchEmbedding}

Keypoints $(p_t, v_t, a_t)$ at each frame are concatenated
($399 \times 3 = 1197$ dimensions) and projected via a learnable linear layer
to the embedding dimension $d = 256$:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{z}_t = \mathbf{W}_{proj} \cdot [p_t; v_t; a_t] + \mathbf{b}
    \label{eq:proj}
\end{equation}
A \textbf{BodyPartAttentionBias} module applies learnable per-keypoint weights
$w_k$ to the input before projection, initialised with domain knowledge values:
hand keypoints (indices 91--132) receive weight 3.0, feet (17--22) receive 2.5,
spine region (5--12) receives 1.8, and face (23--90) receives 0.5. These weights
are trainable, allowing the model to refine the importance of each body region.

\subsection{Transformer Encoder}

Sinusoidal positional encodings are added to $\mathbf{z}_t$, and a prepended
[CLS] token aggregates global sequence information. The encoder stack consists
of:

\begin{table}[H]
\caption{DanceFormer-Large Architecture Parameters}
\label{tab:danceformer}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline
\textbf{Parameter}           & \textbf{Value} \\
\hline
Embedding dimension ($d$)    & 256 \\
Transformer layers           & 8 \\
Attention heads              & 8 \\
Head dimension               & 32 \\
Feed-forward dimension       & 1024 \\
Dropout                      & 0.1 \\
Max sequence length          & 128 frames \\
VideoMAE projection dim      & 1024 $\rightarrow$ 256 \\
Projection head dim          & 128 (L2-normalised) \\
Total parameters             & $\sim$12.3M \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Classification Heads}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Dance head}: Linear layer projecting the CLS token to 8 logits
    (one per dance form).
    \item \textbf{Mudra head}: Per-frame linear layers projecting each temporal
    embedding to 28 mudra logits, supervised by the rule-based mudra labels.
    \item \textbf{Projection head}: Two-layer MLP followed by L2-normalisation,
    producing a 128-dimensional unit vector used by contrastive and metric
    learning losses.
\end{itemize}

\section{Combined Loss Function}

The complete training objective $\mathcal{L}$ is a weighted combination of six
component losses:

\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L} = w_d \mathcal{L}_{focal} + w_s \mathcal{L}_{supcon} + 
              w_c \mathcal{L}_{center} + w_p \mathcal{L}_{push} +
              w_a \mathcal{L}_{angular} + w_m \mathcal{L}_{mudra}
\label{eq:loss}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Focal Dance Classification Loss}

The Focal loss~\cite{lin2017} down-weights well-classified examples,
concentrating gradient updates on hard or minority-class samples:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{focal} = -\alpha_t (1 - p_t)^{\gamma} \log(p_t)
\label{eq:focal}
\end{equation}
where $p_t$ is the predicted probability of the ground-truth class,
$\gamma = 2.0$, and $\alpha_t = 0.25$. Label smoothing of 0.05 is applied
to the target distribution.

\subsection{Supervised Contrastive Loss}

Following~\cite{khosla2020}, the Supervised Contrastive Loss pulls together
all clips of the same class in the normalised projection space:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{supcon} = \sum_{i} \frac{-1}{|P(i)|} \sum_{p \in P(i)}
\log \frac{\exp(\mathbf{z}_i \cdot \mathbf{z}_p / \tau)}{\sum_{a \neq i} \exp(\mathbf{z}_i \cdot \mathbf{z}_a / \tau)}
\label{eq:supcon}
\end{equation}
where $P(i)$ is the set of positive (same-class) samples in the batch and
$\tau = 0.07$ is the temperature.

\subsection{Center Loss}

Learnable class centres $\{\mathbf{c}_k\}_{k=1}^{8}$ are updated via
exponential moving average ($\alpha = 0.5$) during training. The loss
penalises intra-class dispersion:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{center} = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i} \|\mathbf{f}_i - \mathbf{c}_{y_i}\|^2
\label{eq:center}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Inter-class Push Loss}

The Inter-class Push Loss directly targets the confused pairs identified
from the confusion matrix. Let $d_{ij}^{cos} = 1 - \hat{\mathbf{c}}_i \cdot \hat{\mathbf{c}}_j$
be the cosine distance between normalised class centres $i$ and $j$:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{push} = \frac{1}{|\mathcal{P}|} \sum_{(i,j) \in \mathcal{P}} w_{ij} \cdot
\max(0,\; m - d_{ij}^{cos})
\label{eq:push}
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{P}$ is the set of confused pairs, $w_{ij}$ is the confusion
weight (proportional to observed confusion percentage), and $m = 1.2$ is the
target minimum cosine distance. The confused pairs and weights are:

\begin{table}[H]
\caption{Confused Pairs and Push Loss Weights}
\label{tab:confused}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{|l|l|c|c|}
\hline
\textbf{Class A} & \textbf{Class B} & \textbf{Confusion (\%)} & \textbf{Weight $w_{ij}$} \\
\hline
Mohiniyattam & Kuchipudi      & 32 & 3.0 \\
Kathak       & Kathakali      & 19 & 2.5 \\
Odissi       & Bharatanatyam  & 14 & 2.0 \\
Kuchipudi    & Sattriya       & 12 & 1.5 \\
