Inter-class push           & $w_p$ & 0.25 \\
Angular orthogonal         & $w_a$ & 0.10 \\
Mudra cross-entropy        & $w_m$ & 0.40 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\section{Prototype-Based Inference Calibration}

After training, mean class prototype embeddings $\{\mathbf{c}_k\}_{k=1}^{8}$
are computed from the training split and saved. During inference, the final
class probability is a weighted blend:
\begin{equation}
\hat{P}(y = k \mid x) = (1-\lambda) \cdot p^{logit}_k + \lambda \cdot p^{proto}_k
\label{eq:proto}
\end{equation}
where $p^{logit}_k = \text{softmax}(\text{logits})_k$,
$p^{proto}_k = \text{softmax}(s \cdot \hat{\mathbf{f}} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{c}}_k^T)_k$
(cosine similarity scaled by $s = 10$), and $\lambda = 0.4$. This calibration
is particularly effective for the Mohiniyattam--Kuchipudi boundary, where
the two class prototypes become measurably better separated after training
with the Inter-class Push Loss.

