Our approach differs from all prior work in three fundamental ways.
First, we use 133 COCO-WholeBody keypoints compared to the 17-point body
skeleton used by ST-GCN and similar action recognition systems. The 42
additional hand keypoints capture mudra geometry that is the primary
discriminative signal for several class pairs. Second, we train across all
eight government-recognised forms simultaneously, whereas prior dance work
addresses only a single form or static image classification. Third, our
six-component loss function is explicitly designed to address empirically
observed class confusion, rather than using a single cross-entropy loss.

