\chapter{Conclusion and Future Work}

\section{Conclusion}

This project presented NatyaVeda v2, the first end-to-end AI system to
classify all eight Indian classical dance forms from video with 97.49\%
accuracy. The system integrates a multi-tier pose extraction pipeline
(VitPose-Plus, RTMW-x, MoveNet), a 133-point whole-body skeletal feature
representation with MediaPipe hand fusion, VideoMAE-Large appearance features,
and a DanceFormer Transformer classifier trained with a six-component loss
function.

The primary technical contribution is the confusion-matrix-driven loss design:
earlier baseline evaluations identified the most confused pairs as
Mohiniyattam--Kuchipudi, Kathak--Kathakali, and Odissi--Bharatanatyam, which
motivated the Inter-class Push Loss used here. Combined with Supervised
Contrastive Loss, Center Loss, and Orthogonal Angular Loss, the system achieves
measurably better embedding cluster separation than a focal-loss-only baseline.
Prototype-based inference calibration further improves boundary-case accuracy
without retraining.

The engineering contributions --- a fully documented and reproducible
installation pipeline resolving known Windows/Python 3.10 compatibility
issues between NumPy, OpenCV, MMPose, MediaPipe, and TensorFlow; a DanceIsolator
with fast motion-only mode reducing refinement time from 17 minutes to 30
seconds per video; and a unified multi-tier pose extractor supporting hardware
from GTX 1650 to A100 --- collectively reduce the barrier for future work
in culturally specific dance recognition.

\section{Future Work}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Larger dataset}: The current 174-video dataset is sufficient
    for initial training but insufficient for the data-hungry contrastive
    losses. Expanding to 500+ videos per class through curated archival sources
    and data augmentation (synthetic pose jittering, temporal interpolation)
    is the single highest-impact improvement path.
    
    \item \textbf{Graph Convolutional Network fusion}: Replacing or augmenting
    the Transformer temporal encoder with a spatial-temporal GCN that explicitly
    models the kinematic chain (e.g., elbow--wrist--finger dependencies) may
    improve mudra discrimination.
    
    \item \textbf{Real-time inference}: The current pipeline processes
    approximately 4--6 frames per second on a GTX 1650. Optimising through
    TensorRT quantisation, half-precision inference, and frame sampling
    reduction could enable live performance feedback.
    
    \item \textbf{Segment-level predictions}: The current model assigns a
    single label per clip. A streaming decoder that outputs frame-level
    transitions between dance sequences (e.g., sanchari $\to$ padam in
    Bharatanatyam) would enable richer choreographic analysis.
    
    \item \textbf{Cross-form mudra recognition}: Training a dedicated mudra
    recognition model across all forms would improve auxiliary supervision
    quality and enable standalone hasta identification tools for dance education.
    
    \item \textbf{Adversarial robustness}: Evaluating how perspective changes,
    costume occlusion, and low-light performance conditions affect keypoint
    quality and classifier confidence would be important for real-world deployment.
\end{itemize}

